with active sodium transport in ascending limb","Random arrangement of tubules with passive diffusion","Parallel flow in same direction between ascending and descending limbs"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct mechanism involves \u003Cstrong\u003Eparallel flow in opposite directions with active sodium transport in ascending limb\u003C/strong\u003E. The countercurrent multiplier system requires fluid flowing in opposite directions through adjacent tubules (the ascending and descending limbs of loop of Henle), with active sodium transport out of the thick ascending limb. This creates and maintains a concentration gradient in the medulla.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPassive water reabsorption in ascending limb\u003C/strong\u003E - The ascending limb is impermeable to water and instead actively transports sodium out of the tubule.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive sodium transport in descending limb\u003C/strong\u003E - The descending limb is permeable to water but lacks active sodium transport mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERandom arrangement of tubules\u003C/strong\u003E - A precise parallel arrangement is essential for countercurrent multiplication to function effectively.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParallel flow in same direction\u003C/strong\u003E - The system requires opposite flow directions to generate and maintain the concentration gradient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe vasa recta blood vessels also use countercurrent exchange to prevent washing out of the medullary concentration gradient. This allows the kidney to concentrate urine by removing water while maintaining the solute gradient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Countercurrent multiplication in the kidney creates a concentration gradient in the medulla through parallel flow of fluid in opposite directions.","The loop of Henle acts as a countercurrent multiplier by actively pumping sodium out of the ascending limb.","Vasa recta blood vessels use countercurrent exchange to preserve the medullary concentration gradient."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57448"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17673"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57448"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T20:52:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T22:51:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10387"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71978"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https